comments.text: Made this with my Printrbot Simple and PLA. I would not recommend it for others with Simples because the tolerances were not high enough to get a smooth fit, but with a higher-quality printer, it's probably just fine. The pins on the USB port part did not print smooth enough to slide in while maintaining the right amount of friction to stay put, and broke off pretty quickly. We were able to get the Mintyboost into the box and the lid on, but to get the batteries changed, something is probably going to break. Also, the first layer (bottom) of the main box did not fuse together, possibly a result of not having a heated bed and ABS. I am new to 3D printing so some of the issues might have been due to my inexperience, and I do understand the limitations of a $300 printer, but I just want to let other Simple owners know that this might be beyond the capability of our cool little tool. All in all, still a fun project for my teenage daughter and me.

title: CTC Bizer Dual (and others) doors and lid

description.text:
This project started with the hinges I found on this platform. From there it progressed in completely closing my CTC with doors and a lid/top-cover. I planned on adding hinges to the lid as well, but decided to keep it separated from the printer so I didn't need to drill more holes close to the y-axis rod and because the lid, when opened, would need to go further to the back than the position of my printer allows. Now I just take it off and put it aside, when necessary.

I didn't change the hinges, but did redraw them in Freecad. New stl files are attached.
The DXF files are the cutting template for the doors and top-cover plates. The front doors are a bit larger than the front opening, the side doors fit into the side openings. I used 3 mm acrylic which I cut by hand using a special knife. Laser cutting is preferred....
Because of the thickness of the acrylic, I added spacers between the hinges and the doors. 6 mm for the side doors and, in the beginning, 3 mm for the front doors. I later changed them for 2mm spacers for a less tight fit.
I made drill templates for the printer case and for the doors. They can be mirrored by physically turning them around, so you need just one for each door/side.
On the top-cover I used the corner parts as a drill template (Tape it together first to be sure all plates are positioned right)

I screwed everything together using M3 nuts and M3 allen bolts (M3x8, M3x10, M3x12 & M3x16). The knobs allow use of round magnets (12 x 2 mm). You can then put some flat (iron) screw is the case that allow the magnets to snap to the case.

For the top-cover/lid I used brushes from the local hardware store. These brushes are used in (Deltafix) mailbox weather strips. They're easily cut to size and slide in the brackets. This design is a result of the filament holders I decided to use. It allows the filament, and the extruder cables, to go through and still keep the entire setup closed.

All the parts:

Doors:
8x Hinge, Hingebracket & Pin; 2 for each door
4x 2mm spacers; 2 for each front door (3mm spacer for tight fit)
4x 6mm spacers; 2 for each side door
12x M3x12; Front door hinge
12x M3x16; Side door hinge
2x Front door knob
4x M3x8
2x Side door knob
4x M3x10
32x M3 nut

Top-cover/lid:

Acrylic plates:
Top plate 400 x 270 x 3 mm
Front plate 400 x 150 x 3 mm
(2) Side plates 264 x 150 x 3 mm
(2) Back plates 170 x 150 x 3 mm

4x Corner inside & Corner outside; for all 4 top corners
1x Rear bridge inside & outside; joins 2 rear acrylic plates
2x LF (Left Front) + RR (Right Rear) inside & outside corners; bottom corners
2x LR (Left Rear) + RF (Right Front) inside & outside corners; bottom corners
70x M3x12
70x M3 nut

Optional:
2x L+R Brush holders; Left & Right brush holder
1x Rear brush holder: <--

title: Ord Bot Front & Side Foot (Y-Axis Tensioner)

description.text:
This is a marriage of two designs that have been submitted on Thingiverse by dbailey and flurin.  I loved dbailey front foot support but it did not give me the tensioning that i needed.  Additionally, I loved how flurin designed his belt tensioning system, but i found too much upward flex and the side supports limited y-axis travel.  This design uses all the original parts included in the Ord Bot BOM except for the feet.  For the pulley you will need an M5 nut.  The two belt tensioning screws are M4x20.  You will also need 2xM4 nuts.  No support is required.  
Update:  12/3/2013 I added a back foot to support the rear of the machine.  It follows the same design cues as the front foot.
Part was designed in Solidworks.  First layer is .1mm.  Remaining layers are .35mm.  No support.  Top and bottom 5 layers are solid.  The rest is 70% infill.

This is a fruit fly trap lid that screws on to a normal canning / mason jar. This is based on this canning jar lid: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:19105 The fly trap lid pictured was printed with a low, draft resolution on a Mosaic with ProtoParadigm Red PLA. This thing is a part of a collection of things featured in this post: http://www.protoparadigm.com/blog/2012/08/what-to-do-with-a-3d-printer-make-canning-jar-accessories/

Download whichever you need and print it.  There is a regular, and a wide-mouth version available.
After printing, put some bait in a canning jar and screw the lid on.  This bait can be pieces of fruit, fruit juice, or anything else that will attract fruit flies.  As luck would have it, I haven't had any fruit flies around since I finished this (not that I'm complaining), so I haven't had a chance to test it, but I've had good luck with cruder traps of similar design in the past.  Apparently a mix of some fruit juice with just a little bit of vinegar in it is a decent bait.
Place the baited trap near where you have fruit flies.  They should enter through the hole at the end of the inverted cone, and will be unable to escape.

comments.text: I was talking with somebody about a lid that would fit onto a canning jar to trap fruit flies... and then I stumbled onto your design.  It's perfect!  I've been using a glass with a taped on paper cone: not the most pleasant to look at.

comments.text: I made one and it works great! I have captured many fruit flies. I didn't have a canning jar on hand, but I found a clear plastic jar in my cupboard with the same size threads -- can't remember what came in that jar originally. For bait, I found that fruit flies love red wine. I discovered that when I left a glass of red wine on the coffee table for a very short time and came back and found two drunk fruit flies doing the backstroke in my wine. So I use maybe half a teaspoon or so in the jar. If I have a banana or a peach handy I put a chunk of banana or peach skin in also. My fruit flies go out in gourmet fashion! Peaches and red wine sounds like a great way to die to me!

description.text:

The inner surface meets a parabolic ruler and has honeycomb pattern to evacuate spilled liquid.There is a top ring for stop the glass movement.
My model in red ABS took 3 hours at 0,3 layer and 10% infill and have a nice aspect,but
suspect what whit 0,2 the finished will be more slippery.Acetona vapor can help also.

The second thing was not printed yet , but i included here for everyone who wants one original voronoi parabolic coaster , if there is any error or problem let me know , please.

description.text:
This is a beta version of my double extruder with planetary gear. The gear ratio is 1: 4,444. The function is uncertain when all parts are fully tested yet. However functioning prototype I made with only one level very well so this will also work flawlessly.

Main block holding the motors (NEMA 17) has a fastening plate with holes 2 at 88mm distance. This then I adapted the part of sitting on top of my P3Steel frame.

I have designed this for the trains to be printed separately in durable materials. Type ABS or nylon. The remaining parts do I do with a different material. For example, PLA.

You have to cut the output shaft into the stepper motor a little bit of everything to suit.

Remember that it takes 6st planet gears in this!

The design is in the current mode NOT TESTED! Some faults can occur in both the design and text.
Translated with Google Translate, some errors may occur.

Nuts & Bolts

8x M3x25
4x M3x20
4x M3 Nuts
6x M3x15 (actually 11)

2x M5x40

The Extruder things

I used an all-metal extruder kit from AliExpress as the basis of the extruder. The parts that come from there is the bridge to lock the filament feed wheel, slave wheel tightening screw, spring, pins and the nut to sett pressure.
Link to the extruder: https://www.aliexpress.com/item/1Set-DIY-Reprap-Kossel-All-metal-Remote-Planet-Reducer-Motor-Geared-Bowden-Extruder-Alimunum-alloy-for/32454606130.html?spm=2114.13010608.0.0.884ozL

More things

4x 625zz Bearings
2x pneumatic couplings whit m6 threads.
2x NEMA 17 Stepper Motors

And some good grease for the Gears!

Long ago in the deserts of Egypt,there was one 3D printer that changed the world.

Here are three Christmas ornaments made from compounds of dodecahedrons and icosahedrons. The polyhedra were generated so that the principal axes of the coordinate system, x,y, and z, coincided with 3 of their 2 fold axes. Before combining one of the polyhedrons was rotated by 90 degrees around the x axis. ornament_1.stl - two dodecahedrons - the result has octahedral symmetry ornament_2.stl - one dodecahedron and one icosahedron - this is the dual compound - it has icosahedral symmetry ornament_3.stl - two copies of ornament_2 - the result has octahedral symmetry OpenSCAD code is included. George Hart's Virtual Polyhedra Site has some information about compound polyhedra - See
http://www.georgehart.com/virtual-polyhedra/compounds-info.html

The ornaments were printed on a raft with external support.  On my Replicator they took about 3 hours to print using 2 shells and 5% infill.

description.text:
I dissected this Typhoon jet Eurofighter into 4 parts for those who don't have a large build plate or don't want to print any support. Then you can use your favorite glue to put the parts together. This model is published previously by nestor_d.

Tips to have a super flat print:
1- I used non-heated bed with 3M blue tape. Make sure to sand the tape surface with a 150 - 120 grit sand paper before printing. Then dust-off the blue tape sanded surface to remove any paper powder resulted from the sanding process. Also make sure the tape is pressed hard to the build plate so it doesn't peel off.
2- Lower the speed of the first layer to 18 mm/s. This will make it stick better to the build surface . Other layers might be better to be no more than: 26-30 mm/s to have better quality finish.
3- Use PLA with 20% infill.
4- When removing the finished print from bed, remove carefully and gradually with a knife so you don't bend the edges or break it.

If you look at the photo you can tell that i was rushing to put the parts together and i used a low quality glue!. Also the model will look better if you used a filling putty to fill the gaps like: Tamiya Putty (Basic Type)

title: Antenna guard protection cover for FPV camera Eachine TX01 TX02 TX03 installed in JJRC H8 Mini or Floureon H101 mini drones
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This thing is a little remix based on the design "whoop camera mount for eachine TX01" http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1815820 by "sepela" (Oct 9, 2016).

I have created two versions of his antenna guard with less thickness. The first one with 1.6 mm and the second one with 1.2 mm. It was a must to reduce the thickness and the total weight since I needed to insert this guard over the upper body shell of two similar mini drones (Eachine/JJRC H8 mini and Floureon H101) with the idea to protect the antenna of the Eachine TX01 camera that I had installed for fpv (first person view).

The thick of original guard designed by "sepela" is 2.41 mm. I have decided to include his original design with my bundle for ease.

Although I have created these guards for the Eachine TX01 fpv camera, they will fit surely with other similar little cameras or mini drones when you require to insert the guards over the upper body shells of them (not using base mounts for the camera).

I have included two pictures of my modded mini drones where you can appreciate the final result of inserting the new antenna guards. Finally I chose the 1.6 mm version for the Eachine H8 mini (white) and Floureon H101 (red) because it is more robust. As you can see the two terminals of the guard were approched for the insertion within the borders of the upper body shells.

For this kind of modding I recommend using hot-melt adhesive to fix the guards well. Be careful about where you insert the guards to avoid they are touched by the drone blades.

The files available to download are:

  • 1.2mm_antenna_guard_protection_fpv_aio_camera_mini_drone_sxs.stl
  • 1.6mm_antenna_guard_protection_fpv_aio_camera_mini_drone_sxs.stl
  • 2.4mm_antenna_guard_protection_fpv_aio_camera_mini_drone_original_sepela_sxs.stl

description.text:
This is a small bracket to hold an ND filter for the Zerotech Dobby. Care must be taken when positioning the bracket to ensure that it sits squarely over the lens and wholly within the lens assembly. The best way to do this is to use an impact adhesive to give yourself time to move it into position. Stick a piece of ND filter gel onto the back of the inner frame and trim to size. That's it!

Note: I printed this using PLA at 220 deg without any problem but the side walls are thin (about 0.5mm) and so you need to make sure the layers bond properly. I did also try printing using Colorfabb nGen and the side wall peeled away. I then kept the nozzle temp high (220 deg and the fan at 20% and that seems to have worked.

EDIT - I've added a new stl file (and Openscad file) called dobby filter2. This is a slightly wider bracket so as to be able to accomodate a slide into which the official Zerotech ND filter can be stuck.

In my view this is a much better arrangement because the Zerotech filter is far better quality than a bit of ND gel which tends to lose its coating after a while.

So, if you have the Zerotech ND filter, use dobby filter2.stl.

title: DRV8825 compatible servo control for CNC shield with Digispark Arduino

description.text:
This project is intended to provide a simple solution for using servos with CNC and plotter projects based on GRBL Arduino firmware (and CNC shield). Of course it is possible to use a modified GRBL firmware and drive the servo directly from the main Arduino. However, this requires specialized firmware and often specific Gcode instructions.

This project strives to use a Digispark (Attiny85) to imitate the DRV8825 stepper drivers to control the servo. This way you can use generic Gcode and the Digispark takes care of converting the Z axis commands to servo movement. My goal was to make this as simple as possible so anyone can do it. It would also work on other axes, but placement of the module might become less trivial and my main focus was the Z axis (as for 2.5D plotter like movement).

Step 1: Needed parts

Needed: One Digispark module, the included pin header and two pieces of hard wire.
For the software one needs the Arduino IDE, the Digispark drivers and a micro USB cable.

Step 2: Soldering

Solder the pin header on the bottom and the wires on the 5V and the GND pin.

Step 3: Flash the firmware

Use the Arduino environment to upload the included ino file to the Digispark. Instructions on how to set up the Arduino IDE for Digispark can be found on the internet with some googling. Once the firmware is flashed, the USB cable is no longer needed.

Step 4: Put it all together

The Digispark module can be inserted as shown on the photo. The 5V and GND wires can be inserted in the FAULT and GND pins of the DRV socket (as shown in the picture). P0 of the Digispark module aligns with the DRV8825 DIR pin.

The servo PWM pin should be removed from the three-pin dupont socket and connected to the pin that is used for microstepping jumper (M2) because that way it is connected to P4 which does the PWM stuff. If you are not sure which pin on the shiled it is, you can try all six of them without damaging stuf.

Power for the servo can be taken from the CNC shield as shown in the picture. Now you can control the servo with generic Gcode Z commands!

Certainly the movement of the servo is limited to 180 degrees, but it remembers the absolute position, so it is possible to return to zero position. If necessary the startup position (initial value = 90) and the sensitivity (MICROSTEP) can be adjusted in the code.

For heavier servos an external power supply might be a good idea, since the 5V on the CNC shield is powered from the USB port of the computer. For simple servos it should suffice.

comments.text: Nice design.  I have been playing around with the CNC Shield and was curious is you could help answer a question for me if you are running a PWM signal off the board?  If so, what is the voltage range you get off this board (i.e. M3 S0 vs. M3S255)?  Mine is only running from 3v-5v and I guess I am thinking that is should be from 0v-5v?
comments.author: Norton575

comments.text: The Digispark is powered by 5V, but there is a voltage regulator on the board. I'd think the Attiny is running on 3.3V, so the analogue equivalent of the PWM signal should be 0v-3.3V. Of course this only holds for a Hi-Z input. With a voltage divider / pull up on the output you could pull it up to 5V, but the low signal (0V) might rise accordingly.

description.text:
USB-powered soldering irons have become very popular recently and sell on Ebay for less than £5. Their power rating is low (<5W) but their ridiculously low price make them very appealing as portable soldering tools for small components. I thought I'd make a 3D-printed support to hold two of these irons together so I could use them as soldering tweezers.

The files I post here correspond to the first iteration of the design. It is far from perfect but it more-or-less serves as a proof of concept.

It needs support material and prints in about 45 minutes using light infill and fast print settings in an Ultimaker 2+ extended with PLA and a 0.4 mm nozzle.
